Barack Obama is the fourth U.S. president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama is coming to Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to be the fourth U.S. president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize in history.
In addition, he receives the diploma, medal and a $1.4 million check for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The head of the White House arrives tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the Norwegian metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time at all with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple then scheduled a meeting with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its peak with the ceremony at which Obama takes over the prestige prize.
He is the fourth president of the United States, but only the third to receive the prize directly in office.
The White House has already determined that Obama will talk about the Afghanistan war when he takes over the prize.
The president does not want to avoid this issue because he knows that he is taking the prize as a president who is currently at war in two countries.
A few days ago, he intensified the war effort by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gold medal, diploma and check of ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event program will then include a banquet with the President and his wife, with the Prime Minister and another 250 invited guests in addition to Norway’s King and Queen.
Obama was very cautious about the price from the start.
For example, he cited that he felt he didn’t deserve the prize.
He repeated several times that the prize is not just for him, but for all those who aspire to the same values as he.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that this was for him a "call for action".
