U.S. Repetition is a Mother of Wisdom
It’s almost strange with what student aspiration Barack Obama, the president with his call of the smartest, repeats his predecessor’s strategy in the Afghanistan question, which he himself thought was the stupidest.
When he finally sweated out his long-awaited Afghanistan doctrine, it turned out that he wrote it off on the copy paper from the Bush-Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he has even used the name of the Bush Declaration of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "New Forward Path" without hesitation.
Three years ago, he himself criticized the Bush idea of sending out fresh contingent troops into the Iraq plagued by the civil war as a “irresponsible and in their conclusions disastrous decision.”
However, the following months showed that the Bush strategy, based on military recommendations, was the only possible and, to this extent, very successful, and that today the news about Iraq is not talking at all.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, because objectively he left his successor a much more grateful starting point than was expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will repeat itself.
In order to increase the contingent of troops, the military asked him again, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghanistan operation General Stanley McCristal, who even in spite of the subordination habits harshly criticized the turbulent shooters in the White House.
He demanded 40,000 soldiers to reverse the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but did not come up with a better idea and so he cheated the general by 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe, he has pressed the pledge for another 5,000, even though he originally expected at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of the entire Obama strategy is his plan to withdraw the troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and complete this process within three years.
Some doubt that the halved increase will have the same effect as the measure in Iraq.
Despite the fraternal war of recent years, the Iraq society is relatively well structured, its leaders honor the values.
The Afghan situation is characterized by contraindications - no one can be relied on and no agreements are kept.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, who are accustomed to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if they were formally established correctly, remain only shams, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to grow.
The balance of interests between the different ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially because of the ambiguity of the conditions that complicate the influences of Pakistan and Iran even further.
Building a “capable state” which is the minimalist goal of the entire operation is also very unrealistic.
Obama’s strategy’s time horizon is alienated by its voluntarism
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened further and now it is on the brink of the explosion.
Believing that the little soldiers who have erupted into the scream of war over the "early return" can create a miracle here can only be a truly romantic soul, which cannot be impressed by facts.
From a political point of view, the date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, because the Taliban will take this as the indirect confession of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in the fighting in Afghanistan is in decline.
Europe’s politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is linked to the war in the Hindukusch mountain foreland.
Another possible factor that can radically influence the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, there is a very serious question for the United States as to whether the problem cannot be solved with troops.
This question must be answered during the period when America moves on to the victory withdrawal from Afghanistan after Obama.
But any solution will also mean a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is the fact that there are still three years to go until the presidential election, and so there is still enough time for him to resort to another strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
