Czech discovery: a substance that also works for ‘steeled’ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on the viruses that are already resistant to medication.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not act as strongly on common virus variants as one of the existing drugs.
AIDS cannot be cured.
However, patients can prolong their life and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus proliferation also results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which no more drugs are effective.
The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, the VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way for dealing with virus resistance.
They have demonstrated that the substances referred to as metalocarborans act on the protein that is responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus proliferation in a different way than all drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists come up with new “improved” compounds that have been prepared based on the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multifaceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Insidious and Persistent Virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus splitting caused by the HIV protease, no mature infection virus particles would arise.
When we turn off HIV protease, we also turn off the multiplication of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in the press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe entire series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further altered.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in test tubes, including against their resistant variants obtained by HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metalocarborans on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as with the clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical forms, makes metalocarborans interesting compounds for further research aimed at developing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
