Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters have voted for a minarets construction ban and worries about the alleged Islamization of Europe are widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a well-founded and well-thought-out report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of Europe’s most declared secularized societies – and integrated.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work: "Why the French don't love headscarves" (2006), an elegant and densely argumentative study of a dispute that divided and occupied the country over a decade and a half, and the impact of which can still be seen today.
Bowen’s latest book offers a wider and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what the politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls them, “Islamic spaces.”
He is a good listener, he reflects debates between teachers and students about the questions that bother them the most.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or a city hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use a interest-based banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profane affairs, he claims, that make up daily life, quite contrary to the political dramas that concern the media.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of whom have a known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arab-Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate about how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen on the other in a modern secular society.
You don’t have all the arguments on your side.
Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists Bowen interviewed are mostly disagreeable with their salafist counterparts – advocates of purist Sunni Islam, which is associated with Saudi Arabia – who today show a small but influential presence among Europe’s Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questions the extent to which French political decision-makers (and the intellectual elite so passionately guarding the separation of church and state) really feel committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may experience harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who in turn had to make their historic compromise with secular republicanism.
He recognizes more of a “strengthening of the value screws” than a growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book you are inclined to say "Yes, but not yet".
