UN Group Drafts Emissions Reduction Plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterized by wild poses and mutual accusations -- once again focused on Friday with the release of a document that records an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with industrialized nations having to face the biggest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final policy agreement on greenhouse gases, has shown both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it has been seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that runs out as more than 100 top politicians from around the world arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a UN working group specifically for this purpose, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to the poor countries so that they can master global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrialized and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of the global temperature rise should be that policymakers would contribute.
The process is given great flexibility, according to John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN’s leading climate protection representative, Yvo de Boer, has called “the big picture.”
It shows the outline of a possible agreement in which industrialized nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also gave the talks a boost on Friday by pledging to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change – from overcoming floods and droughts to avoiding deforestation.
Friday still brought the same verbal fireworks that the talks had determined last week.
U.S. climate commissioner Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if they are not funded by industrialized nations.
This train announced that the Obama administration would be on a tougher line with China than it was with the Bush administration less than two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without larger emerging economies standing up and taking action, Stern said, who also complained that the text does not go far enough to ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern made his statement an hour after China’s Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said that the leading American climate negotiator either lacked “reason” or was “highly irresponsible” by him, saying earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China master global warming.
As the future economic direction of the great world powers is at stake, breaking lines have opened up both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle relates equally to saving individual economies, as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their corresponding commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the great powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of braking greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to take more aggressive action to hold countries with very high greenhouse gas taxes accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game that will lead to a new economic dominance, according to Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change advisor for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say the talks will lead to a political agreement at best.
The Alliance of Small Island States with 43 members presented a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the small island states’ offensive “exerts political pressure on the entire political process,” partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks got a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues still need to be clarified before the arrival of government leaders to reach an agreement.
High-ranking representatives, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, escaped from their planes and rushed through the corridors of the Bella Center to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to set out claims to be negotiated during the next week.
The sheer size of the assembly -- 13,000 people go in and out of the congress center every day, guitar-playing activists are having nighttime shows in which they make fun of the countries they think are betraying and selling, and draft contracts are hand-to-hand instead of emailing -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: Almost all major ministers are here now and from Wednesday there will be 60 government leaders in Copenhagen.
We are coming to the upper league, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president of global politics of the organization Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
