The boundary between dream and hallucination
In our overly conscious world, imaginary experience is unfortunately usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Clinic for Psychiatry and Psychotherapy of the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also contains positive, creative - delusion is also a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroid experience form, a special form of traumatically altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the experiencer considers real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state in retrospect.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with self-destruction and world loss, for example, by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with an imaginary world that is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a world change takes place, but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
