75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among the younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women on the fertility and career of women in Spain.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market limited due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not, and if so, what kind of profession they practice.
Those of them who do no other work outside the house, only work half-days or do not have a fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a permanent job, especially in the public sector, postpone the creation of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the age group between 35 and 49 with a permanent job have their first child on average only 3.7 years after moving in, a figure that increases to 4.1 years for women with a permanent job who have taken longer to achieve this and who have only pulled in and realized the first child much later.
Furthermore, the type of work has a major impact on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar in terms of conception," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account at the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference was also seen in women of the same age.
For example, the women in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, depending on whether they had only primary school or higher education, on average, each became mothers with 25.1 or 32.1 for the first time.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with a master’s degree get married before their first permanent employment and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school degree do it exactly the other way around and look for a permanent employment and marry afterwards and then have their first child, Delgado notes.
