Support for braking maneuvers in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the anti-lock braking system ABS and as with the stability control ESP, the auxiliary systems for braking in emergencies must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already compulsory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, for the rest of the vehicles a caring period was set until the end of February 2011.
The European Union's decision is aimed at improving the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many crashes due to their working methods.
The object of the emergency braking assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking maneuver which the system detects on the brake pedal on the basis of the braking strength executed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident were unable to step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, engages with maximum force in the braking system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking operation.
According to a study by the EU, every year up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents could be prevented with personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
The vehicle is then equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
When the driver responds, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
