New Vehicle Assessment Programmes
These days of storms and accidents not only the car workshops deserve
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are towed to the workshops, where an appraiser must assess the damage caused and the cost of the repair.
Not a single accident is the same and calculating the cost of parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
Calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros by hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer science tools, it is a matter of minutes.
That’s why almost 100% of reviewers use this type of system.
The accident assessment and repair service providers collect the information they receive from the manufacturers in order to process it afterwards and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American Solera group, is the market leader; 80% of all expert opinions are created with their products.
The other two companies competing with GtMotive and Eurotax in the tool market for reviewing and drafting a report.
Working with the data that the manufacturers provide is anything but simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Audatex sales manager, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each of them providing the information in a different format.
Furthermore, the volume of data to be processed is increasing, to the point that in the last five years even more versions, variants and engines have been introduced on the market than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car comes on the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a tedious task, because every single one of the thousands of vehicle parts must be catatolized and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphic image on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much-sold model, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure proceeds swiftly.
If this is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has full information on 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of the vehicle fleet on the roads, it is over 99%.
In order to carry out documentation work and to produce databases, Audatex has eight centers (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) distributed worldwide and each of them specializes in specific brands.
The national headquarters are located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics professionals) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests €90 million a year in the development of these databases.
Every month, they record 2.5 million data and their customers get the updates every other day.
